{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17628311","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17628311"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:56:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:56:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17214"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17214","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17214"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0.84,0,0,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9904"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74804"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9904","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9904"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17214"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60291"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"32"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"131"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"1127"},{"type":"tags","id":"2308"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23231"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23234"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74804","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74804"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 37-year-old female presents to the Emergency Department with a headache she described as the \u201cworst headache of my life.\u201d The headache started recently, is severe, continuous and generalised. The patient previously had a loss of consciousness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears distressed. Her pulse rate is 95/min, blood pressure 165/95 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. She is alert but has marked neck stiffness. There are no focal neurological deficits.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Idiopathic intracranial hypertension","Subarachnoid haemorrhage","Intracerebral haemorrhage","Cerebral venous sinus thrombosis","Ischaemic stroke"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with the classic triad for \u003Cstrong\u003Esubarachnoid haemorrhage \u003C/strong\u003E(SAH): thunderclap headache, meningism, and loss of consciousness. The sudden onset of what patients describe as the \u0027worst headache of their life\u0027 is highly characteristic of SAH and requires immediate investigation with CT brain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIdiopathic intracranial hypertension\u003C/strong\u003E presents with chronic headache and visual symptoms in young, overweight women. The onset is gradual rather than sudden, and loss of consciousness would be unusual.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntracerebral haemorrhage\u003C/strong\u003E presents with focal neurological deficits depending on the location of the bleed, along with headache and reduced consciousness. The absence of focal deficits makes this less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECerebral venous sinus thrombosis\u003C/strong\u003E can present with headache and altered consciousness, but the onset is usually more gradual over days. Seizures are common, and there are often predisposing factors such as pregnancy or thrombophilia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIschaemic stroke\u003C/strong\u003E presents with focal neurological deficits corresponding to the vascular territory affected. While headache can occur, it is not usually the predominant symptom, and meningism would be unusual.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Sudden onset severe headache described as \u0027worst ever\u0027 with meningism is highly suspicious for subarachnoid haemorrhage until proven otherwise.","Loss of consciousness in the context of sudden severe headache suggests raised intracranial pressure and requires urgent neuroimaging.","The classic triad of sudden severe headache, meningism and loss of consciousness has a high sensitivity for subarachnoid haemorrhage."],"references":["Marcolini E, Hine J. Approach to the Diagnosis and Management of Subarachnoid Hemorrhage. West J Emerg Med. 2019 Mar;20(2):203-211. doi: 10.5811/westjem.2019.1.37352. Epub 2019 Feb 28. PMID: 30881537; PMCID: PMC6404699.","D\u0027Souza S. Aneurysmal Subarachnoid Hemorrhage. J Neurosurg Anesthesiol. 2015 Jul;27(3):222-40. doi: 10.1097/ANA.0000000000000130. PMID: 25272066; PMCID: PMC4463029.","Bigal ME, Lipton RB. The differential diagnosis of chronic daily headaches: an algorithm-based approach. J Headache Pain. 2007 Oct;8(5):263-72. doi: 10.1007/s10194-007-0418-3. Epub 2007 Oct 23. PMID: 17955166; PMCID: PMC2793374","Ahmed F. Headache disorders: differentiating and managing the common subtypes. Br J Pain. 2012 Aug;6(3):124-32. doi: 10.1177/2049463712459691. PMID: 26516483; PMCID: PMC4590146"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60291"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17214"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60291","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60291"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-27T11:14:46+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-01T19:01:54+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9904"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74804"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/ap